# Fableland — Foe System GDD

Design doc for the enemy/foe layer: types, stats, scaling, AI, skills, and evolution.
Covers everything that makes a fight work, from the moment a foe spawns to the moment it
dies (and what it leaves behind).

Implementation target: `Scripts/Foes/` (refactor from the current single `Scripts/Enemy.cs`).
First landed in **v0.4.0**.

---

## 1. Two-axis difficulty

A fight's difficulty is the product of two independent systems:

| Axis | Source | What it controls |
|------|--------|-----------------|
| **Map node level** (1–6) | Which node the player chose on the overworld | Objective complexity — wave count, foe count, win conditions, boss presence |
| **Foe level** (1–8) | How many days have passed (see §2) | Enemy stat scaling + skill access for every foe in every fight |

A player who grinds level-1 nodes still faces escalating foe levels as days pass.
A player who rushes a level-4 boss node on day 35 faces level-5 foes during a complex
objective. The two axes multiply: you can't out-grind the clock, and you can't out-rush
the stats.

---

## 2. Foe levels (day-based scaling)

Foe level is determined **purely by the current day**. It applies to every foe that
spawns, regardless of which map node the player is on.

| Foe Lv | Days | Difficulty | Skills unlocked | HP mult | ATK mult | SPD mult |
|--------|------|-----------|----------------|---------|----------|----------|
| 1 | 1–10 | **Fairytale** (童话般的) | — (patrol only) | ×1 | ×1 | ×1 |
| 2 | 11–20 | **Mundane** (平凡的) | Aggro (sight) | ×1.2 | ×1.2 | ×1.2 |
| 3 | 21–30 | **Mundane** (平凡的) | Sight improved | ×1.5 | ×1.5 | ×1.2 |
| 4 | 31–35 | **Challenging** (崎岖的) | Skill 1 | ×2 | ×1.5 | ×1.2 |
| 5 | 36–40 | **Challenging** (崎岖的) | Skill 1 | ×3 | ×1.5 | ×1.5 |
| 6 | 41–45 | **Demonic** (险恶的) | Skill 1 + Skill 2 | ×3 | ×2 | ×1.5 |
| 7 | zone 6 — LV5 nodes | **Hellish** (地狱般的) | Skill 1 + Skill 2 | ×4 | ×3 | ×1.5 |
| 8 | zone 6 — LV6 core | **God-Forbid** (神惧) | Skill 1 + Skill 2 | ×5 | ×3 | ×2 |

**Zone 6:** past the singularity the day is unknowable (`???`), so foe level is fixed
by the **node** instead of the day: the five `XX-5` fights spawn level-7 foes, the
`XX-6-1` core fight spawns level-8 foes. (The planned elapsed-time scaling of zone-6
defenders — `MapGDD.md` §8a anti-stagnation — remains TBD and would sit on top of this.)

**All multipliers are from base stats, not cumulative.** A level-8 Crab has 5× base HP,
3× base ATK, and 2× base SPD — calculated directly from the base values defined per foe
type (§3–4), not chained through previous levels.

"Skills unlocked" gates which abilities the foe has access to (see §3–4 per type).
Levels 2–3 add the sight/aggro system; levels 4+ unlock active skills one at a time.

---

## 3. Crab Foe

The grounded melee bruiser. A simplified port of the Unity BaseFoe/CrabFoe.

### Base stats

| Stat | Value |
|------|-------|
| Base HP | 70 |
| Base ATK | 18 |
| Base SPD | 90 px/s |
| Gravity | 2048 px/s² (Units.Gravity) |
| Contact range | 44 px |
| Contact cooldown | 0.9 s |
| Contact knockback | 260 px/s |
| Contact stun | 0.25 s |
| Hit radius | 26 px |
| External damping | 1200 px/s² |
| Burn DoT | 14/s |

### Passive — Soft Shell

Receives **200% damage** (2×) from any hit whose source is within a **60° cone above**
the crab (centered on the upward vertical). This rewards aerial attacks and plunging
strikes.

### Patrol

Moves horizontally in a random starting direction. On wall contact, turns around.

### Aggro (level 2+)

When the player is detected (see Sight), moves toward the player horizontally.

### Sight (level 2–3)

- **Shape:** 8×3 m rectangle, **ground-anchored** (extends upward from the crab's feet).
  Centered horizontally on the crab.
- **Check interval:** every 1 s.
- **De-aggro:** 3 consecutive misses → return to Patrol.

### Sight improved (level 3+)

- **Shape:** 12×5 m rectangle, same ground-anchored rule.

### Skill 1 — Spawn (level 4+, passive, on death)

On death, spawns **2 crabs** at `current level − 2`. The skill only exists at level 4+
(§2), so spawned crabs are always level 2 or higher (level 4 → two level-2 crabs,
level 5 → two level-3, … level 8 → two level-6). A level-3 crab that **evolves** to 4
mid-fight gains the skill. Spawned crabs **cannot themselves spawn** (a foe created by
Spawn ignores this skill — no grandchildren).

Spawned crabs appear near the parent's death position (small random offset).

### Skill 2 — Jump (level 6+, 5 s cooldown)

Triggers when **aggro'd** and **either**:
1. The player jumps, **or**
2. The player is within 3 m (96 px).

The crab jumps to the **same height as the player's current jump**. Does **not** deal
landing damage (pure repositioning / anti-kite tool).

---

## 4. Seagull Foe

The aerial harasser. No gravity, momentum-based movement, zoning tools.

### Base stats

| Stat | Value |
|------|-------|
| Base HP | 35 |
| Base ATK | 18 |
| Base SPD | (accel-based, see Passive) |
| Gravity | **none** (ignores gravity) |
| Contact damage | none (does not deal passive contact damage) |
| Hit radius | 20 px |
| External damping | 600 px/s² |

### Passive — Flight

- Does **not** receive gravity.
- Direction-changing **acceleration = 1/3 of the player's** (`PlayerGroundAccel / 3`).
  This gives the seagull momentum — it can't instantly reverse, creating a window for
  the player.
- Turn rate applies horizontally only; vertical position is maintained during patrol
  and adjusted only by skills.

### Patrol

Flies at a fixed height until it reaches **100 m** (3200 px) from its spawn point, then
turns around and flies back. Height is set at spawn (configurable, default ~3–5 m above
ground).

### Aggro (level 2+)

When the player is detected (see Sight), accelerates horizontally toward the player's
X position. Vertical position is maintained (the seagull doesn't dive during basic aggro).

### Sight (level 2–3)

- **Shape:** 60° cone, 10 m length, facing the **direction of movement**.
- **When stationary:** retains last facing direction.
- **Check interval:** every 2 s.
- **De-aggro:** 3 consecutive misses → return to Patrol.

### Sight improved (level 3+)

- **Shape:** 120° cone, 12 m length.

### Skill 1 — Poop (level 4+, 5 s cooldown)

When **aggro'd**: drops a poop projectile that falls with gravity. On reaching a surface,
it **lingers for 3 s**, dealing **30 base damage** on contact. The lingering poop is a
hazard — it zones the player and can stack with multiple seagulls.

Damage: 30 base (× ATK multiplier from foe level). Does the poop deal damage mid-air on
direct hit? **Yes** — direct hit during the drop also deals 30 base damage.

### Skill 2 — Dash (level 6+, 10 s cooldown)

When **aggro'd**: the seagull **stops moving for 1 s** and **turns red** (telegraph),
then **dashes 15 m** (480 px) **at 30 m/s** (0.5 s) horizontally toward the player's
current X position. **Pierces through** the player (does not stop on contact). Deals
**50 base damage** on contact during the dash.

Damage: 50 base (× ATK multiplier from foe level).

---

## 5. Evolution (in-combat)

A foe that is **not eliminated within 25 s** of spawning **evolves** to the next level.

### Rules

- **+1 foe level** (e.g., level 3 → level 4).
- A foe can evolve **at most once**.
- Level 8 foes **cannot evolve** (already at cap).
- **HP:** max HP re-derives from base (`newMax = baseHP × mult(new)`); current HP is
  ratio-preserved, then the foe heals 30% of the new max:
  `hp = min(newMax, hp × mult(new)/mult(old) + 0.30 × newMax)`.
- **No interruption** — evolution happens instantly mid-action. The foe does not pause,
  channel, or reset its current behaviour.
- **Visual tell** (deferred): the foe grows larger, changes color, or swaps sprite.
  For now a brief flash or tint change is sufficient.

### Design intent

Evolution punishes passive play — if the player kites indefinitely without committing
to a kill, the foe escalates. The 30% heal means the player keeps most of their progress
but the fight gets harder. Combined with spawn-on-death for crabs, an evolved crab that
dies at level 5 spawns level-3 babies instead of level-2 — the threat cascades.

---

## 6. Sight & aggro system (shared)

All foes share the same sight/aggro state machine:

```
PATROL ──(player in sight)──▶ AGGRO ──(3 consecutive misses)──▶ PATROL
```

### Sight check

- Each foe type defines its sight shape, check interval, and improved variant (see §3–4).
- A sight check runs on a per-foe timer (1 s for Crab, 2 s for Seagull).
- "Miss" = player is not inside the sight shape.
- "Hit" = player is inside → immediately enter AGGRO.
- 3 **consecutive** misses while aggro'd → return to PATROL. A single hit resets the
  miss counter.

### Aggro behaviour

- Crab: move horizontally toward player's X. Stays on ground.
- Seagull: accelerate horizontally toward player's X. Maintains patrol height.

### De-aggro

After 3 consecutive misses, the foe resumes its Patrol behaviour from its current
position. The miss counter resets to 0 on re-aggro.

---

## 7. Loot & drops (hook only — content TBD)

Every foe has a virtual death hook that fires before `QueueFree()`:

```
OnDeath() → spawn loot (override per type) → QueueFree()
```

Reserved loot types for future implementation:

| Drop | Trigger | Effect |
|------|---------|--------|
| Heal orb | % chance on kill | Restore 15–30 HP |
| Ult charge orb | % chance on kill | +200–500 ult charge (Ult system TODO — TBD registry) |
| Wonder core(s) | Chance on kill / mission mechanics | The run currency (`ITEMS.gdd` §1.2, `NODES.gdd` §5.3) |
| Status cleanse | Rare drop | Clears OnFire/Frozen |

The architecture supports drops without knowing what they are — each foe type's
`OnDeath()` override instantiates whatever pickups it needs. Crab's override also
handles the Spawn skill before calling the base loot logic.

---

## 8. Boss foes (TBD)

Design reserved for a future update. Placeholder notes:

- Bosses use `NodeKind.Boss` map nodes (level 4 world boss, level 6 core boss).
- Distinct foe types (not just scaled-up crabs/seagulls).
- Phased behaviour, unique skill sets, arena modifiers.
- Boss HP bar at top of screen (separate HUD element).
- Guaranteed loot drop.

---

## 9. Architecture overview

```
Scripts/Foes/
├── BaseFoe.cs         // shared: HP, scaling, sight, aggro FSM, evolution, status effects,
│                      //   defense calc, external velocity, hazard interaction, loot hook,
│                      //   ult-charge crediting, damage popups
├── CrabFoe.cs         // ground physics, rectangle sight, Jump, Spawn-on-death
├── SeagullFoe.cs      // no-gravity flight physics, cone sight, Poop, Dash
└── FoeStats.cs        // per-level multiplier table, evolution data, helper: StatsForLevel()
```

`BaseFoe` inherits `CharacterBody2D`. It provides the physics loop, status effect
handling (fire/frozen/burn), damage reception (defense multiplier, knockback, stun,
hitflash, camera shake), and the sight/aggro FSM. Subclasses override:

- `InitFoe()` — set base stats, sight shape, patrol behaviour
- `UpdatePatrol(dt)` / `UpdateAggro(dt)` — movement per state
- `Skill1()` / `Skill2()` — active skills (guarded by level gating in base)
- `OnDeath()` — spawn babies, drop loot, then `QueueFree()`
- `DrawSight()` — debug-draw the current sight shape

The existing `Scripts/Enemy.cs` is replaced by this hierarchy. `Enemy.tscn` is either
replaced or becomes a generic foe scene with the script swapped per type.

### Level-gating skills

`BaseFoe` checks `CurrentLevel` before allowing skill use. Skills are registered with
a `minLevel`; the base `_PhysicsProcess` only calls `Skill1()` / `Skill2()` if the foe's
current level meets the threshold.

### FoeStats lookup

```csharp
public static class FoeStats
{
    public struct LevelStats { public int Level; public float HpMult, AtkMult, SpdMult; }
    public static LevelStats ForLevel(int level);          // 1–8
    public static bool HasSkill1(int level);               // level >= 4
    public static bool HasSkill2(int level);               // level >= 6
    public static bool HasImprovedSight(int level);        // level >= 3
    public static bool HasAggro(int level);                // level >= 2
}
```

---

## 10. Foe ↔ Map integration

When the player enters a combat node on the map, the arena loads with:

1. **Node level** (1–6) → decides the fight's objective (wave count, foe count, win
   condition, boss presence). *This is the fight-designer's knob.*
2. **Current day** (1–45) → decides every spawned foe's **foe level** via the table
   in §2. *This is the difficulty-curve knob.*

A level-1 combat node on day 35 spawns level-5 foes with a simple objective. A level-4
boss node on day 12 spawns level-2 foes with a complex objective. The player balances
pushing deeper nodes against letting days accumulate.

**Authored map spawn contract (v0.7.0):** a combat map carries a per-hardship crab/seagull
weight table (level 0 = its default) and optional enemy-spawn row limits. The periodic spawner
ticks every **4 s**, filters crab/seagull types that lack an eligible map marker, then makes the
weighted choice. The selected marker is the foe's nest/spawn origin; map-defined crab limits use
`cellY <= crabMax`, while seagull limits use `cellY >= seagullMin`. Seashore uses 50/50 and
`crabMax=4`, `seagullMin=5`.

---

## 11. Arena foe cap

- **Hard cap:** 6 foes on screen (raised from the current 4 to accommodate spawn-on-death).
- **Spawn-on-death ignores the cap** — if a crab dies and the arena is at cap, the 2
  baby crabs still spawn (otherwise the skill is trivially negated). The cap only gates
  the GameManager's periodic spawn timer.
- **Evolution is unaffected by cap** — it modifies an existing foe, not a new spawn.

---

## 12. Decisions log

- **HP scaling uses base-relative multipliers, not cumulative.** A level-8 foe's HP is
  exactly `baseHP × 5`. This keeps the curve flat enough that combat times stay reasonable.
- **Crab skills swapped** (Spawn = skill 1 / on-death, Jump = skill 2 / active) so early
  game doesn't introduce spawn cascades before the player has tools.
- **Seagull dash pierces** rather than stopping on contact — it's a swoop, not a tackle.
- **Spawned crabs cannot spawn** — infinite chains are funny exactly once, then they break
  the game.
- **Sight shapes:** Crab = ground-anchored rectangle (vertical escape), Seagull = movement
  cone (positional outplay). Different evasion tactics per foe type.
- **Evolution heals 30%** (not 100%) so the player's progress isn't erased, only dampened.
- **Poop lingers 3 s** (up from the initial 0.5 s) — long enough to zone but short enough
  that the arena doesn't fill permanently.
- **(v0.3.7) Zone-6 foe levels are per-node** (LV5 → 7, LV6 core → 8); the day table
  ends at the singularity.
- **(v0.3.7) Spawn's level-1–3 bullets deleted** — the level-4+ gate is authoritative,
  so spawns are always level-(N−2) ≥ 2; evolution is the only path for a lower crab to
  gain the skill.
- **(v0.3.7) Seagull dash speed fixed at 30 m/s** (15 m in 0.5 s, after the 1 s red
  telegraph). Note the 100 m patrol turnaround exceeds the ~62 m standard arena — a
  patrolling gull effectively wall-turns.
- **(v0.3.7) Evolution HP formula canonized:** ratio-preserved, then +30% of new max,
  capped at new max (see §5).
- **(v0.3.7) WonderPage → wonder core.** The loot hook drops the run currency; the old
  page-based win condition was prototype-0 history.
- **(v0.5.0) Skill dispatch implemented as per-frame `UpdateSkills(dt, player)` with
  `Skill1Ready`/`Skill2Ready` gates**, not the §9 parameterless `Skill1()/Skill2()`
  calls — trigger conditions need per-skill state (telegraphs, cooldowns), so the base
  loop hands control to the subclass each frame instead of invoking blindly. Level
  gating (`FoeStats.HasSkill1/2`) is unchanged and still authoritative inside the
  Ready gates. Functionally equivalent to §9; recorded so the doc matches the code.
- **(v0.5.0) Seagull top flight speed = 160 px/s (5 m/s)** — the GDD was silent;
  tuning placeholder, revisit on a feel pass.
- **(v0.5.0) Wave/arena composition prototype defaults** (per-world composition tables
  still TBD): every ambient/wave slot rolls 60% crab / 40% seagull; ambient cap 6 with
  a 3 s trickle (the cap gates only the trickle, per §11); Slaughter wave size =
  3 + node level, final wave at foe level +1 capped at 8.
- **(v0.5.0) Placeholder boss = scaled-up Crab** (HP ×8, ~×2 footprint, beefier
  contact; one add-wave of 2 foes at foe level −1 when the boss hits 50% HP) until the
  §8 boss kits are designed. Outer BOSS wins grant Yukai's Rope; the starting-realm LV4
  also grants TwistedReality. Recruitable boss protagonists remain TBD.
